al inflows, next is the regional factor (important for EMEs); the global factor explains a small fraction of the volatility.<br/>Weak explanatory power of macro variables for capital flow volatility, but factor differentiation helps with the fit.<br/>The explanatory power of macro variables for the idiosyncratic factor is limited.<br/>Determinants of the global factor: VIX, FFR, U.S. term spread. That is, U.S. variables.<br/><br/>Quotations: &quot;Given that we do not aim to explain capital flows as such in terms of macroeconomic de- terminants, but focus on the idiosyncratic parts only, our results appear acceptable. Moreover, with the dominant role of the lagged endogenous variable it would be too ambitious to expect a larger explanatory power from other variables. It is in this sense that wethink our results compare favourably with those presented in the literature. As a matter of fact, however,we cannot completely rule out that the idiosyncratic factors to some degree reflect noise.&quot; p. 117<br/><br/>&quot;The primary responsibility for dealing with large and volatile capital flows remains with domestic policymakers.&quot; p. 121<br/><br/>How this article influence my research:<br/>It shows that most of the variation in capital inflows is driven by country-specific components, which seems to conflict with other studies Sarno et al. (2016).<br/>The limited explanatory power of macro variables for the idiosyncratic component: missing stock returns (Guo 2016)?, relevance of mixed frequencies? For example, to explain portfolio flows include past stock market returns (Liang Guo, 2016), local term spread, FX changes.<br/><br/>Extend the results of the paper to outflows and types of borrowers for 'other' flows (banks, government, private), include volatility, mixed frequencies.<br/><br/>Add an additional layer: global, region, type-of-flow, type-of-borrower, idiosyncratic. What about: global, region, type-of-borrower, type-of-flow, idiosyncratic<br/><br/>For example, for type of borrowers, is the effect of global and idiosyncratic factors the same on 'other flows' depending if the receiver is the government, banks, or private firms?},
